  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 素琴刻背志
  author: 李奎報
  language: lzh
  text: 風俗通曰。琴者。樂之統也。君子所常御。不離于身者也。予非君子人也。尙蓄一素琴。絃㢩不具。猶撫而樂之。家有見而笑者。因具五絃以與之。予受之不辭。於是。彈爲長側短側。大遊小遊。凡皆如意也。昔陶潛有無絃琴。寓意而已。予以區區此一蛹絲。要聽其聲。則其不及陶潛遠矣。然予自樂之。何必効古人哉。酌一杯。弄一曲。以此爲率。是亦遣一生之一樂也。遂刻其背曰。白雲居士琴。欲使後之見者。知某之手段所甞經也。
korean:
  title: 소금의 등에 새긴 지
  author: 이규보
  language: kor
  text: 풍속통(風俗通)에 이르기를, “거문고는 음악을 통합하는 것이니, 군자가 항상 지니고 몸에서 떼지 않는 것이다. 나는 군자는 아니나, 한 개의 소금(素琴)을 두었으니, 현(絃)과 적(㢩)은 구비하지 않았어도 오히려 어루만지면서 즐긴다. 어떤 손님이 보고 웃으며 다섯 줄을 갖추어 주거늘, 나는 사양하지 않고 받았다. 이에 긴 곡조 짧은 곡조 큰 놀이 작은 놀이로 타보니 다 생각하던 것과 같았다.옛날 도잠(陶潛)은 줄 없는 거문고로 뜻만 부쳤을 뿐이었는데, 나는 가느다란 이 한 가닥 명주실에서 그 소릴 듣기를 구하니, 도잠에 미치지 못함이 멀구나. 그러나, 나는 스스로 즐거워할 뿐 어찌 반드시 고인을 본받으리오. 술 한 잔 먹고 한 곡조 타는 재미로 나날을 보내니, 이 역시 한 세상 한 가지 낙이었다 하고, 드디어 거문고 등에 글을 새기기를, ‘백운거사금(白雲居士琴)’이라 하여, 뒷날 보는 자로 하여금 아무의 손에 거친 것을 알게 한다.” 하였다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1080_030_0010&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: An Inscription on the Back of a Plain Guqin
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Record of Customs tells us: 'The guqin is the very soul of music, the constant companion of the gentleman, never to be parted from his side.' I am no gentleman, yet I have kept a plain guqin, its strings and bridges incomplete. Still, I run my fingers over it and find joy. A visitor saw it once and smiled, then gave me five strings to complete it. I accepted without hesitation. And so I played—long passages and short, grand themes and subtle ones—all flowing as I wished them to.

    Once, Tao Qian had a stringless guqin, and with it he merely suggested meaning. But I—I seek to hear actual sound from these few strands of silk. How far I fall short of that sage! Yet I do not grieve. Why must I always imitate the ancients? A cup of wine, a melody played—this is how I pass my days, finding in it one small happiness for a lifetime.

    So I carved these words upon its back: 'The Guqin of the White Cloud Recluse'—that those who see it in ages to come might know whose hands have worn this instrument smooth.
  footnotes:
    - Tao Qian (陶潛, 365-427), known as Tao Yuanming, was a renowned poet and recluse of the Eastern Jin dynasty. He famously owned a stringless guqin and played it as a purely symbolic gesture, caring nothing for actual sound—a metaphor for his detachment from worldly concerns.
    - The 'White Cloud Recluse' (白雲居士) is Lee Gyu-bo's pen name, reflecting his scholarly retirement and contemplative approach to life.
    - Lee Gyu-bo (1168-1241) was a Goryeo-era scholar-official who, like many Korean literati, admired the aesthetics and philosophy of Chinese antiquity while developing his own voice.
